{"cursor":"4275","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{multiple issues|\n\n\n\n\n}} {{Infobox weapon\n| name = Aruval image = caption = Thirupatchi aruval origin = Tamil Nadu, India\n| type = Sickle\n\n| is_ranged = is_bladed = yes is_explosive = no is_artillery = yes is_vehicle =\n| no is_missile = no is_UK =\n\n| service = used_by = wars =\n\n| designer = design_date = manufacturer = unit_cost = production_date = number =\n| variants =\n\n| spec_label = weight = length = part_length = width = height = diameter\n| = crew =\n\n| cartridge = cartridge_weight = caliber = barrels = action = rate = velocity =\n| range = max_range = feed = sights =\n\n| breech = recoil = carriage = elevation = traverse =\n\n| blade_type = hilt_type = sheath_type = head_type = haft_type =\n\n| filling = filling_weight = detonation = yield =\n\n| armour = primary_armament = secondary_armament = engine = engine_power =\n| pw_ratio = transmission = payload_capacity = suspension = clearance =\n| fuel_capacity = vehicle_range = speed = guidance = steering =\n\n| wingspan = propellant = ceiling = altitude = depth = boost = accuracy =\n| launch_platform = transport =\n}} The 'aruval' () is a type of billhook from India, particularly common in the\nsouthern state of Tamil Nadu. It is used both as a tool and a weapon. Tamils\nrevere the weapon as a symbol of Karupannar. Other times it is associated with\nsouth Indian gangsters, especially in popular culture.\n\nAn aruval usually measures 3-6 feet in length. The tang in the short-handled\naruval is usually a full-length rat-tail and handles are usually round, made\nwith wood from neem or acacia species. Aruvals with longer handles rarely have\nfull tangs and are typically used by farmers to chop grasses or harvest grains\nas the longer handles make it easier to work from an upright position. Blades\nare mostly straight with a curve towards the end, allowing it to function as a\ngrabbing tool. The straight portion of the blade is also used for cutting,\nlike a standard knife. While farmers typically employ the sickle-like kathir\naruval for harvesting crops, a longer variation called the veecharival is used\nfor clearing through wooded areas. The veecharival was also used as a weapon\nand continues to function as such for the purpose of self-defense in rural\nareas or gang warfare in cities. When not in use, the weaponized aruval was\nworn on the back, with the blade pointing downwards and the handle just behind\nthe user's head. Some aruvals, used in worship of the Kaval Deivam, are as\nlong as six feet.\n\n{|\n|\n|\n|}\n","linknr":126,"url":"Aruval","recorded":1375090658,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Aruval&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Aruval&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Aruval&action=edit","/wiki/Talk:Aruval","/wiki/File:Crystal_Clear_app_kedit.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Crystal_Clear_app_kedit.svg/40px-Crystal_Clear_app_kedit.svg.png","/wiki/Wikipedia:Layout","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Aruval&action=edit","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edi